\section{Geometric Interpretation of a Vector}
\label{ssec.geovector} \markright{\ref{ssec.geovector}
\titleref{ssec.geovector}}

In this section we begin the discussion on vectors by first
introducing their visualization. A vector in two space or three
space can be visualized as a directed line segment. A vector is
different from scalars in that a vector has both a magnitude and a
direction. It is often represented as an arrow, with the arrow
head indicating the vectors direction. The tail of the vector is
called the {\bf initial point}\index{initial point}. The tip is called the
{\bf terminal point}\index{terminal point}.

There are many different notations used to denote a vector. In
textbooks, it is common to see vectors in boldface, to
differentiate them from scalar quantities. This notation will be
used here. For your assignment questions however, it is
impractical to attempt to bold vectors, so you can either
underline the symbol $(\underline{w})$ or put a small arrow over
the top $(\overrightarrow{w})$.

Two vectors of the same length and direction are said to be {\bf
equivalent}.  Note that the initial and terminal points need not
be the same.  The following figure shows two equivalent vectors.
