\section{Summary}\label{ssec.sum4}\markright{\ref{ssec.sum4} \titleref{ssec.sum4}}

 {\bf Keywords: Cauchy-Schwarz inequality;
distance; dot product; Euclidean inner product; Euclidean norm;
equivalent vectors; $n$-tuple; negative vector; norm; orthogonal; scalar;
scalar projection; terminal/initial points; unit
vector; vector; vector projection; vector space; zero vector.}

In this section, vectors have been introduced. These are
quantities which can be  thought of as arrows in 2- or 3- space;
they have a magnitude and a direction. We have defined the dot or inner product and
the orthogonality of vectors.  Orthogonality has been used to derive the equation of lines and planes.
Equations of figures in 2 and 3 dimensions have been derived as determinants.  Vectors need not be
limited to 3 space however; a vector in $\real{n}$ is
represented as an $n$-tuple.  We have defined vector addition,
subtraction and multiplication by a scalar.  We have used these
operations to compute the length of a vector, and to find the
distance between points.  We have also defined the dot or inner
product on vectors in $\real{n}$

